The death toll from Sunday's Himalayan earthquake rose to over 549 in Nepal as reports  arrive from remote areas.
Blocked or severely damaged roads and roads flooded by  monsoon rains have severely hampered relief efforts.
Dharan, near Katmandu, was the hardest hit area.
There, over 131 victims were found,  most in unstable brick and mud homes.
Police Inspector Adhikari said bulldozers razed  over 50 severely damaged houses.
Prime Minister Shresta called the disaster, "the biggest  calamity to strike Nepal."
Indian officials claim the death toll is 200 or less, but opposition politicians and the press  say 400 to 1500 perished. 
